<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tuesday has become Social Conscience Night. Assignment tells the ghastly
story of 'social cleansing' in Colombia where death squads with names such
as 'Kan Kill' and 'Black Hand' set out to clean up the streets by murdering
prostitutes, drug addicts and street children. It is said that tramps were
lured to a university campus, murdered, and sold to medical students for
dissection. One, who was clubbed almost to death, came round in a room full
of corpses and escaped to alert the police ..who tend to be a part of the
problem instead of the answer (7.45 BBC2).
Undercover Britain found itself a game 71-year-old woman willing to spend
two months with a camcorder filming secretly in a succession of old people's
homes in the Liverpool area. Three of the homes were run by people with
criminal records and a fourth accepted her even though it was registered as
men-only (9.00 C4).
The people with buckets at busy junctions who rush out when the lights go
red and start making your windscreen opaque are the subject of 40 Minutes
(9.50 BBC2).
</TEXT>
