FT  01 FEB 94 / People: Friedman moves from Stoy to Arthur Andersen
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Brian Friedman is joining Arthur Andersen, the UK's fourth largest
accountancy firm, after jumping ship from Stoy Hayward, the tenth.
Friedman, who said his move from Stoy was 'amicable', will head a new pay
and employee benefits practice, drawing on his experience as head of Stoy
Benefit Consulting.
The move is significant because his role will be to help build up the
discipline for the firm around the world and not just in the UK.
Most Andersen disciplines have by contrast been led from the US, where the
firm was founded. The UK practice recently took the lead in developing a
worldwide insolvency practice.
Jim Wadia, Andersen's managing partner in the UK, expects the UK employee
benefits' practice to be billing more than Pounds 3m within two years; and
the worldwide practice Dollars 15m-18m.
Andersen already carries out similar work in France, Spain and the US. It
was the first UK accountancy firm to devise its own profit-related pay
scheme for staff, since mirrored by other firms including Stoy.
The UK team working with Friedman will include 20 professional staff drawn
from the tax and other existing practice areas, and is likely to begin
hiring new staff.
