FT  01 FEB 94 / Prison officers urged to fight criminal justice bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Delegates from the Prison Officers Association were yesterday urged to mount
an intensive campaign against government legislation which they fear will
neuter their trade union rights.
Mr Brian Caton, association vice-chairman, said the government's proposed
criminal justice reforms were an attack on the POA's democratic right to
represent prison workers and would only perpetuate troubled industrial
relations.
Delegates at a meeting, held at the Trades Union Congress headquarters in
London, were told they should lobby their MPs to change the criminal justice
and public order bill. Clauses in the bill make it an offence for anyone to
induce a prison officer to withhold his services and for any officer to
refuse to perform a duty imposed under prison rules.
The association says the measure will have 'profound consequences for free
collective bargaining' because it will allow the home secretary to regulate
pay. It will also enable parts of a prison to be managed separately by
different private companies, and require prison officers working in the
state sector to transfer to private jails if necessary.
