<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Consumer spending is forecast to rise 17%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumer spending is expected to increase by 17 per cent in real terms
during the next five years, Mintel, the market research organisation, says
today.
Mintel says the largest spending growth sectors are likely to be household
and garden products, medical and school fees, and insurance and pensions.
Falls in unemployment and base interest rates and low levels of inflation
should lead to higher disposable incomes between 1993 and 1998, with
spending on home and security taking priority as the recession ends, the
report says.
An upturn in the housing market is forecast to stimulate spending on garden
products (up 36 per cent during the next five years) and hardware (up 35 per
cent). House purchase and alterations expenditure is set to rise by 30 per
cent.
Spending on medical and education fees is likely to increase by 31 per cent,
while insurance and pensions spending is forecast to grow by 26 per cent. Mr
Peter Ayton, Mintel's head of research, said there was increasing public
concern about the need to prepare for old age and ill health 'in the face of
dwindling government resources'.
The popularity of home entertainment will be maintained over the period,
with sales of brown goods such as televisions and hi-fi equipment, set to
increase by 35 per cent, the report says. Interest in healthier lifestyles
will increase spending on fruit and vegetables, while soft drinks will
continue to be the fastest-growing part of the drinks sector.
The highest growth areas in consumer spending over the past year have been:
education fees; shoes, clothing and furniture repair; medical insurance;
house contents and building insurance. Expenditure in all these areas grew
by more than 10 per cent in 1993, the report says.
Overall, housing accounted for the largest part of consumer spending last
year, as it has in previous years.
A total of Pounds 88.4bn - 22.2 per cent of household expenditure - went on
housing. Next came transport (Pounds 48.8bn, 12.2 per cent of expenditure),
then food eaten at home (Pounds 43.8bn, 11 per cent).
A 10-year analysis by Mintel of spending patterns shows some changes in the
shape of household budgets. Spending on food eaten at home, heating,
lighting and power, domestic appliances and drink now each account for a
smaller share of household budgets than in 1983.
The proportion of spending on housing has increased from 20.1 per cent to
22.2 per cent. Other spending which has increased its share of the household
budget includes insurance and pensions, medical and educational fees, and
household services such as cleaning.
Over the 10-year period average gross household income increased from Pounds
12,490 to Pounds 23,533. Stripping out inflation, this represents a real
increase of 14 per cent, says the report.
Mintel, however, also points to a growing polarisation of income. The
top-earning 20 per cent of households increased their share of Britain's
total household income from 35 per cent in 1979 to 40 per cent in 1992.
At the other end of the scale, the share of total income taken by the
lowest-earning 20 per cent of households fell from 10 per cent in 1979 to
slightly more than 5 per cent in 1992.
British Lifestyles 1994. Mintel, 18-19 Long Lane, London EC1A 9HE. Pounds
895.
</TEXT>
