<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Dormobile comes to an end
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Dormobile, once a prominent name in the motor industry, came to an end
yesterday when its 200 staff were dismissed by a liquidator at the factory
gates in Folkestone, Kent.
The company, which for more than 20 years produced a successful range of
minibuses and motor caravans that were frequently used in television and
film (above), went into voluntary liquidation days before it was due in
court to fight a bid to have it compulsorily wound up.
The 200 workers had agreed to work for Pounds 50 a week, a quarter of their
normal pay. Dormobile's problems have been mounting for 12 years since
production of the Bedford chassis-based van ended when the design became
obsolete. It shifted emphasis to produce bigger, 29-seater buses based on
Iveco Ford and Mercedes chassis. Until last week it was producing around six
buses a week at Pounds 24,000 each. The company had orders worth Pounds 3m
for buses but was unable to convert the orders into vehicles.
