<DATE>940201
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Managers attack quality of training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Employers would like more official help in weeding out poor providers of
training, on which they are estimated to spend more than Pounds 18bn a year,
according to an Industrial Society survey published today, Lisa Wood writes.
The survey says half of Britain's managers believe a significant amount of
the staff training they pay for is 'very poor'.
Much more than a third of the 531 managers surveyed felt that increased
regulation was desirable. Half of them agreed that there should be some kind
of system to licence approved trainers. Respondents did not give opinions as
to who should provide the regulation.
At present the market for training is largely unregulated, although some
training and enterprise councils - the government-backed training bodies in
England and Wales - provide lists of 'approved' consultancies for
initiatives such as Investors in People, the programme which seeks to help
employers link training more effectively to business needs.
The society, which exists to promote best personnel management practice and
is a large provider of training, describes the concern over training quality
as 'alarming'. But it does not support a licensing system, which it says
might be bureaucratic.
Instead, it calls for training bodies to draw up agreed criteria to help
employers judge the effectiveness of trainers.
Mr Andrew Forrest, the society's human resources director, said a more
fundamental issue was that while employers spent a lot of money on training,
many of them did not know exactly what they wanted from a course and so it
was more than likely they would not be satisfied with the outcome.
The vast majority of employers, he said, had no system in place to specify
their training needs or measure the results. Employers, he said, should
think more carefully about why they sent people on courses and consider
whether other forms of training might be more appropriate.
Training Trends No 11. The Industrial Society Sales Unit, Quadrant House, 49
Calthorpe Road, Edgbaston, Birmingham B15 1TH. Pounds 30.
</TEXT>
