<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Output wavers but trend remains upward
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Manufacturing output fell back in January but remains on an upward trend,
says a survey published yesterday by the Chartered Institute of Purchasing
and Supply.
The survey's index result is based on responses from purchasing managers at
manufacturers, and is designed to give an early indication of changes in
economic activity. The index dropped from 54.6 per cent in December to 49.1
per cent in January, its lowest level since January 1993.
The drop to below 50 per cent signalled an overall decline in manufacturing
output. But the institute said this mainly reflected seasonal factors.
'The demand for goods, especially consumer goods, tailed off after
Christmas,' the survey said.
The index, which has been running for almost two years, is not yet
seasonally adjusted.
The employment index also dropped - from 50.2 per cent in December to 47.5
per cent in January - but the institute said that much of the contraction
could be attributed to the release of temporary staff 'as the busy seasonal
period finished'.
The outlook for manufacturers is encouraging. A significant number of
purchasing managers interviewed reported strong growth in new orders in
January, particularly in export markets.
The managers' optimism was also reflected in the stocks of purchases index,
which rose from 47.1 per cent in December to 50.9 per cent in January. The
institute reported that a considerable number of companies began to rebuild
stock levels after the end of the year.
</TEXT>
