<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Foreign outlay on property 'up 70%'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Overseas investors increased their spending on UK commercial property by 70
per cent to Pounds 2.2bn last year, providing a further stimulus to the
fast-recovering British property market.
German, Middle Eastern and Far Eastern investors led the surge of investment
in UK property, according to a report published yesterday by DTZ Debenham
Thorpe, chartered surveyors.
The resurgence of overseas interest in UK property, after two years of
decline, was mainly inspired by the devaluation of sterling, the falling
costs of borrowing and the high investment yields available on property.
German investors, who spent a total of Pounds 700m, were the most prominent
source of overseas finance. Middle Eastern investors spent Pounds 350m, much
of which came from wealthy private individuals. Far Eastern investors spent
Pounds 440m, 60 per cent of which was accounted for by Hong Kong and China.
Just over half the money invested by overseas buyers went into central
London, leaving Pounds 400m for Greater London and Pounds 475m for the
regions.
DTZ Debenham Thorpe said it expected overseas buyers to play a less
important role in the UK property market this year, although their total
spending was likely to remain at about Pounds 2bn a year for the forseeable
future.
Overseas Investment in UK Property 1993. Research &amp; Information Services,
DTZ Debenham Thorpe, 44 Brook Street, London W1A 4AG. Free.
