<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Prison officers urged to fight reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Delegates from the Prison Officers Association were yesterday urged to mount
an intensive campaign against government legislation which they fear will
neuter their trade union rights.
Mr Brian Caton, association vice-chairman, said the government's proposed
criminal justice reforms were an attack on the POA's democratic right to
represent prison workers and would only perpetuate troubled industrial
relations. He said that a rise in lawlessness in jails had coincided with
the prison service's drive towards efficiency savings.
In the past five years, Mr Caton said, the prisons had witnessed nearly
30,000 assaults by prisoners on staff and fellow inmates, more than 13,000
drug finds, over 200 suicides, 79 hostage incidents and more than 100 riots
or protests.
He said: 'The cost to the taxpayer of this unchecked lawlessness amounts to
Pounds 1bn.'
He condemned the criminal justice and public order bill currently going
through parliament, which he said did nothing to address the 'horrendous
spiral of violence' in prisons.
Delegates at a meeting, held at the Trades Union Congress headquarters in
London, were told they should lobby their MPs to change the bill. Mr David
Evans, POA general secretary, said it 'neuters the right of prison officers
to carry out their lawful authority.'
Key clauses in the bill make it an offence for anyone to induce a prison
officer to withhold his services and for any officer to refuse to perform a
duty imposed under prison rules.
The association says the law will have 'profound consequences for free
collective bargaining' because it will allow the home secretary to regulate
pay. It will also enable parts of a prison to be managed separately by
different private companies, and require prison officers working in the
state sector to transfer to private jails if necessary.
The association has already had its right to take industrial action
withdrawn because of a court ruling last autumn.
</TEXT>
