<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Part-timers hit the exchequer's pocket: Philip Coggan, in
the third of a series on the tax base, looks at changes in the labour market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The changes in the UK labour market during recent years have been much
trumpeted - the old pattern of males working from nine to five, five days a
week, is no longer the norm. New jobs, when created, are increasingly
part-time or involve self-employment and are often taken by women.
The implications of this for Britain's tax base have not received much
attention, but the change in working practices could be a factor in the
government's funding difficulties.
A number of the 'supply-side reforms' made by the Thatcher administration
were designed to encourage the growth of part-time and low-paid employment.
But the proportion of the income of part-time workers taken in tax will be
smaller than from their full-time colleagues because of the system of
allowances. For example, an individual can earn Pounds 3,445 a year before
paying income tax, and in the 1993-94 tax year pays a rate of only 20 per
cent on the next Pounds 2,500 of income.
The effect of this can be quite substantial. While an individual earning a
salary of Pounds 12,000 will pay Pounds 2,001.25 in tax, two people earning
Pounds 6,000 a year each will pay a combined total of just Pounds 1,002.50.
Similar shortfalls can occur with National Insurance. In the current tax
year, employees only start paying National Insurance when they earn Pounds
56 a week. Once they pass that threshold, they pay 2 per cent on the first
Pounds 56 and 9 per cent thereafter (up to Pounds 420 a week). So an
individual earning Pounds 12,000 a year will pay Pounds 876 in National
Insurance contributions; two people earning Pounds 6,000 each will pay a
combined NI bill of just Pounds 672.
Furthermore, any employee who works fewer than 15 hours a week does not have
to be covered by employers' National Insurance. There is thus a strong cost
incentive for employers to keep working hours below that level.
The impact of replacing full-time workers with part-timers might be even
greater than the above example suggests. Replacing one full-time employee
with two part-time employees working the same hours may reduce the overall
salary bill.
As Mr Steven Webb of the Institute for Fiscal Studies points out:
'Part-timers not only work fewer hours, they get lower rates for doing so.'
Over the past decade, there has been a gradual substitution of female for
male, and part-time for full-time, workers.
According to the Department of Employment, in March 1983 there were 9.05m
female employees (excluding the self-employed, the armed forces and those on
government training schemes); in September 1993, there were 10.55m. During
the same period the number of males in employment fell from 11.98m to
10.88m. Meanwhile, between March 1983 and September 1993, the number of
people in part-time employment rose from 3.96m to 5.5m, while those working
full-time fell from 16.57m to 15.39m.
A further development is the growth of self-employment, which has risen from
2.21m to 2.99m between the above dates. Schedule D revenues (which reflect
tax on the self-employed) have gradually been increasing their proportionate
contribution to income tax receipts.
But the self-employed have a more generous National Insurance system and
have more opportunity to offset expenses against their tax bills. They are
likely to pay less taxes than salaried individuals with the same earnings.
Not all the arguments run in the same direction. It may be that
labour-market flexibility and the growth of self-employment will bring more
people into the workforce than would otherwise have been the case. If the
economy is working more efficiently, both output and tax revenues will be
increased by the changes.
Furthermore, the tax philosophy of the Thatcher government, to reduce
headline rates while eliminating allowances, may have increased overall
revenue by bringing more people into the tax net. A good example would be
the taxation of company cars. The switch from direct to indirect taxation
also means that part-time workers are simply paying tax by a different
route.
Nevertheless, the logical implication of the labour market changes is that a
pick-up in growth could generate less additional income tax revenue than in
the past.
If so, those in full-time employment will need to bear the greater burden of
direct taxation, and the government could find that growth does not so
automatically lead to tax cuts, as in the 1980s.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
    P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
