FT  01 FEB 94 / Gummer rejects shopping schemes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, yesterday demonstrated his
determination to revitalise urban centres by refusing planning permission
for two out-of-town retail developments.
He also signalled a tougher line on town-centre planning by refusing
permission for a shopping development on the site of the former cattle
market in Ludlow, Shropshire, as the design was not sympathetic with its
surroundings in a 'special, historic town'.
Mr Gummer told the 80th anniversary celebrations of the Royal Town Planning
Institute that he would be making a series of announcements in the next few
months as part of an 'urban quality initiative'.
He said: 'At the heart of the sustainable development strategy is the
question of urban quality.
'Improving urban quality means encouraging the re-use of land in our cities.
It means adapting buildings that form part of the familiar townscape for the
uses people expect to find in their towns and cities.'
The out-of-town applications which Mr Gummer rejected were for outline
planning permission for a supermarket and petrol station on the edge of
Ludlow, and for a sub-regional shopping centre at Duxford, near Cambridge.
Plans for a shopping centre beyond Cambridge's green belt were drawn up in
the late 1980s to ease congestion in the city centre.
