<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Public staff face private envy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Private-sector workers believe that their counterparts in the public sector
are overpaid and under-worked, unpublished polls by the Trades Union
Congress show.
Private-sector workers think civil servants are 'paper pushers' on an
average salary of Pounds 30,000, compared with the reality of closer to
Pounds 15,000.
The detailed research of attitudes in the private sector, by Opinion Leader
Research, found the greatest hostility reserved for local government
white-collar workers. Few in the private sector could describe what local
government staff do, and average pay for a local authority secretary was put
at Pounds 18,000, 30 per cent more than the true figure.
There was more sympathy for emergency service workers and nurses and
teachers, although the latter are thought to have over-long holidays.
Most of those polled could not describe the government's public-sector pay
policy and did not know of any TUC campaign against the proposed three-year
pay bill freeze.
Quite a large proportion did, however, support the idea of a one-day
public-sector strike against the policy of pay restraint. That is almost
certain to be rejected today at a TUC meeting of public-sector union leaders
to discuss the next stage in the campaign against the pay freeze.
According to polling details which the TUC did release yesterday, two-thirds
of people believe the government's clampdown on public-sector pay will hit
the quality of services. Seven out of 10 believe that the effect will be
reduced living standards for workers in the public sector.
The number employed in the public sector fell by nearly 1.5m over the past
decade, according to official figures published yesterday.
Partly as a result of privatisation the public-sector share of the total
workforce fell from 29 per cent in mid-1983 to less than 22 per cent 10
years later. During the same period the number of people in the private
sector rose from 16.6m to 19.2m. The workforce as a whole grew from 23.6m to
24.9m.
The Central Statistical Office's analysis of public-sector employment shows
that women in the National Health Service and NHS Trusts made up 78 per cent
of the public-sector workforce. Of female public-sector employees, nearly
half worked part-time, compared with 6 per cent of males.
</TEXT>
