keen to receive bids to buy agencies and quangos, or for running them under
contract.
The seminar was also attended by Mr Stephen Dorrell, the Treasury minister.
Mr Waldegrave told the seminar the government would in future invite the
private sector to participate in discussions over the setting up of
agencies. The same would apply to reviews of the 92 agencies, which normally
take place every three years.
In both cases, the government must examine alternatives to agency status.
The alternatives are abolition, privatisation, putting the agency under
private management or contracting-out its work to the private sector.
Similar arrangements will apply to almost 1,400 non-departmental public
bodies, the quangos that deliver services on behalf of government. The
computer operations of Itsa, the Department of Social Security's information
technology agency, are to be offered to the private sector, the government
said yesterday.
Some 2,000 staff, mostly based in the north-west and north-east, will be
affected.
The successful contractor will win business worth some Pounds 100m a year.
