<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Banks make cautious moves to try to win more friends
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Customers expecting an instant transformation in the behaviour of banks as a
result of the new code of banking practice, to be published next week,
should not hold their breath.
The fact it is called a 'second edition' of the code rather than a new
version shows it is not a fresh start, but a refinement of the original code
published two years ago.
Specific improvements will be made. These include plans for banks to
introduce pre-notification of charges for personal customers, and tighter
rules on how they may obtain the consent of their customers to pass on
account details to other parts of the group.
The governing principles of the code - that banks should be fair and
reasonable in their dealings with customers - are to be incorporated in the
code itself, to promote greater compliance with the spirit as well as the
letter of the guidance. Banks will also do more to ensure that both
customers and staff are aware of the code's provisions.
The changes are the result of a tortuous process. An independent advisory
committee led by Sir George Blunden, a former deputy governor of the Bank of
England, made recommendations late last year to a working party representing
banks and building societies.
That working party, comprising members from the British Bankers'
Association, the Building Societies Association and the Association of
Payment Clearing Services, came to its own views on the recommendations. The
new code will be published by the three associations, after consultation
with their own members.
Sir George believes that bankers have improved since work on the original
code began in 1990.
'I have been much impressed with the change in attitude of the banks between
four years ago and now, about the importance of a good code in improving
bank-customer relationships,' he says.
Those involved in the discussions say the banks rejected the review
committee's advice in only one minor respect, and in many areas -
pre-notification of charges included - they went beyond the recommendations.
The commercial logic for banks of improving relations with personal
customers - or at least with certain types of customer - has become
increasingly evident. Competition is intensifying for customers who are
confident enough in the service from their bank or society that they look to
those institutions for a range of financial services.
But the code can also conflict with those competitive pressures. The annual
report from Sir George's committee on its enforcement, published last July,
for example criticised Barclays Bank which had been requiring customers
applying for new accounts, credit cards or loans to sign forms consenting to
account information being given to other companies within the Barclays
group.
Barclays has said that it will change its ways, and produce new forms
enabling customers to 'opt in' to agreeing that information about their
account may be distributed, but these are not yet in use.
The conflict is one example of the limitations of the voluntary system,
particularly as it is intended to act as a substitute for statutory
guidelines.
The code resulted from the work of the Jack committee in the late 1980s on
banking law. That recommended a statutory code of practice for banks'
relations with private customers. The government did not want to legislate
on this, and agreed with the associations that instead there should be a
voluntary code based on recommendations from an independent advisory
committee.
The Treasury's continuing ability to legislate has given it influence in the
discussions on revising the code. Its wishes have been heeded sufficiently
for the government to continue to back the current system.
In the absence of a move to legislation, the voluntary arrangement has some
value for customers as the best code they have. For banks and societies it
has a value also in diffusing pressure for a more draconian system.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6021 National Commercial Banks.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
