<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / CSA address rules to tighten
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to tighten rules governing the Child Support Agency to
ensure that addresses of separated parents are not disclosed.
The announcement by Mr Alistair Burt, social security minister, came as the
government told MPs that proposed changes to the way the agency functions
are expected to take effect from next Monday.
The new arrangements - due to be debated by parliament this week - will
effect a number of changes, including enabling absent fathers facing big
increases in maintenance payments to pay the bills in stages over 18 months.
They follow a government review of the CSA conducted late last year after
widespread anger over the formula used to calculate maintenance.
The government yesterday remained under fire over the agency from all sides
of the House of Commons, including its own back benches.
Mr Burt rebutted a call by Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security
secretary, to consider following an Australian precedent by introducing a
system of review officers. The Australian system was 'far more rough and
ready', the minister said.
Mr Burt's pledge on not disclosing addresses followed a warning by Mr Kevin
Hughes, Labour MP for Doncaster North, that the leaking of confidential
information while investigating fathers refusing to pay for their children's
upkeep could lead to violence.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
