<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Creditors set for Maxwell group payout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Creditors of Maxwell Communication Corporation are expected to receive a
first payout from the company in March this year, says a report just
circulated by the administrators.
Mr Mark Homan, Mr Colin Bird, Mr Alan Jamieson and Mr Jonathan Phillips, the
joint administrators to MCC from accountants Price Waterhouse, said they
expected a 'substantial' distribution by next month and another during the
second quarter of the year.
They placed the total amount to be distributed as being in the range of 28p
to 43p in the pound, plus up to a further 8p if a series of litigation
claims were successful.
This represents an increase in estimated realisations from the previous
range of 23p to 40p, reflecting greater proceeds from sales of MCC's US
businesses than initially expected.
The figure for realisations from litigation has fallen from 9p in previous
reports. It includes potential legal actions against professional advisers
to MCC and against insurers, and over disputes covering Dollars 137m in
shares in Berlitz, the language school and publishing company, and Dollars
140m paid to five banks in the three months before the company entered
administration.
The report estimates that total assets available for distribution to
unsecured creditors are in the range of Dollars 1.03bn (Pounds 680m) to
Dollars 1.35bn, and the value of unsecured claims is in the range of Dollars
3.17bn to Dollars 3.62bn.
It says legal actions have begun for claims on 14 insurance policies taken
out by MCC through the brokers Willis Corroon, as well as against insurers
who have not paid up on a personal accident policy taken out on the life of
Robert Maxwell.
The creditors' report suggests the administrators are still seriously
considering suing the principal advisers to MCC, 'in particular' Coopers &amp;
Lybrand, the auditor. It says the administrators have interviewed audit
staff and examined papers in the UK and US.
The report says a decision will be taken this month on whether to begin
legal action in connection with transactions involving the disposal of
property to companies which transferred the assets to Liechtenstein trusts
or private Maxwell companies.
The administrators are also considering actions in connection with the sale
of a subsidiary of the publisher Macmillan in December 1988, from which
Dollars 119m was transferred to private Maxwell companies.
Total professional fees paid so far are Dollars 65m, which Mr Homan said
should be seen in the context of the total realisations in MCC achieved so
far and likely in the future.
</TEXT>
