<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Lawson backed for top job at OECD
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The British government is backing Lord Lawson, the former chancellor, to be
the next secretary-general of the Paris-based Organisation for Economic
Co-operation and Development.
The job of running the 'club' of 24 industrialised nations falls vacant in
September when Mr Jean-Claude Paye, the present secretary-general, completes
his second five-year term of office. Mr Paye, a former French diplomat, is
again a candidate for the job, as is Mr Donald Johnston, a Canadian Liberal
politician.
British government officials said yesterday that Lord Lawson was ideally
qualified, pointing out that he was a strong supporter of international
economic co-operation when chancellor.
The OECD secretary-general has a tax-free salary of FFr91,000 a month (about
Pounds 125,000 a year), a flat in the elegant 16th arrondissement of Paris
and a chauffeur-driven car, and can qualify for additional allowances. The
succession will be discussed by OECD ambassadors, aiming at a consensus by
June.
Lord Lawson's candidature is unusual because he has a heavyweight political
background, whereas recent OECD heads have been bureaucrats. However, there
is a growing tendency to put strong political figures into such posts - for
example Mr Peter Sutherland's appointment as director-general of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
Mr Paye has earned praise for his stewardship of the OECD, but has adopted a
low profile at a time of dramatic upheaval in the world economy. The OECD,
which serves as a source of advice and a forum for exchanging views among
its members, is also facing change, with Mexico negotiating membership and
South Korea, Hungary, Poland, the Czech Republic and Slovakia anxious to
join.
</TEXT>
