<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Post Office presses for sell-off decision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Post Office yesterday urged the government to change its ownership
'without delay' if privatisation is favoured as the best way to give it more
commercial freedom.
Mr Bill Cockburn, chief executive, said: 'If privatisation is the means by
which the government decide to give us more freedom, let's have it as soon
as possible. Any further delay would be very damaging.'
His outspoken remarks, which came on the eve of today's inquiry into the
Post Office by the Commons trade and industry committee, are aimed at
injecting a note of urgency into the government's decision-making process.
They also reflect concern that, unless a bill to privatise the corporation
is put forward in the next session of parliament, it is unlikely to take
place before the next general election.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, is to appear before the
committee today. He is expected to tell MPs that the government's own review
into the Post Office, which has taken 19 months, is nearly complete.
The Post Office hopes today's committee meeting will put pressure on Mr
Heseltine to bring the DTI review to an immediate conclusion in favour of
privatisation.
Post Office managers have always said the ownership of the corporation is a
matter for the government. However, they are understood to have told
ministers that privatisation is the only option which would enable them to
take on international competitors.
Mr Heseltine is understood to have ruled out privatisation for the
foreseeable future. Mr Cockburn and Mr Mike Heron, Post Office chairman, are
expected to press him to give the corporation more commercial freedom.
Mr Heron said restrictions were giving foreign rivals the opportunity to
poach key customers and forge ahead.
'Government restrictions on the Post Office are giving aggressive foreign
sales teams the opportunity to poach key Royal Mail customers,' he said.
'This could lead to higher prices, lower quality and the threat of job
losses.'
He will today tell MPs that the days when UK companies automatically looked
no further than the Royal Mail for mailing services have gone.
The Mail Users' Association, which represent more than 100 businesses,
described the government's new financial targets for the Royal Mail - equal
to a 2p tax on every letter - and its refusal to give it more commercial
freedom as 'a recipe for disaster'.
The Post Office Users National Council warned that the Post Office faced a
crisis if the government did not change the financial regime under which it
operates.
Decision in the post, Page 18
</TEXT>
