deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, yesterday flew to Tokyo at the
head of a mission whose purpose is to conclude a 'framework' trade agreement
with Japan before Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa visits Washington on
February 10-12.
Talks in Washington last week by senior officials from both countries failed
to produce any breakthrough on US demands that Japan accept sector-by-sector
targets for greater access to Japan by US goods and services. It was agreed,
however, that follow-up talks at ministerial level in Tokyo would be
necessary.
The US continues to insist officially that Japan improve market access and
stimulate its economy. However, the political confusion that has gripped
Japan over Mr Hosokawa's attempts to bring about political reform - resolved
in a compromise bill only last weekend - has hampered US attempts to settle
the framework issue. President Bill Clinton is seen as unwilling to
undermine a prime minister whose reformist policies he has supported.
