<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Turkish central bank chief quits after policy row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISTANBUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Turkey's economy, already under pressure following last week's devaluation,
was dealt another setback yesterday with the resignation of the central bank
governor, Mr Bulent Gultekin.
The resignation will further undermine the credibility of the battered
conservative-led coalition, and that of the prime minister and chief
economic policy-maker, Mrs Tansu Ciller, at a critical time as the country
approaches municipal elections in March.
Mr Gultekin is a widely respected economist and a former professor of public
finance at Wharton School in the US. His departure will further fuel the
public impression of deep divisions in the government over economic policy.
The governor was only appointed to the job last August.
The immediate cause was unclear yesterday although Mr Gultekin is understood
to have been particularly angry at Mrs Ciller's reported remarks that it was
the central bank that was to blame for 12 per cent devaluation.
Mr Gultekin warned yesterday of 'political and economic tensions in the
coming days'. He said he had used all the monetary instruments available to
him to see off a crisis, but had been 'left alone'. He urged the government
to adopt a 'reliable and believable' stabilisation programme.
'Instead of a market economy, we have a situation where every sector expects
everything to be provided by the state,' he said.
Like Mrs Ciller's clash with the former central bank chief, Mr Rusdu
Saracoglu, her differences with Mr Gultekin revolve around disagreement
about how to finance the budget.
While tapping international debt markets, the prime minister has relied on
short-term central bank advances, wary of fuelling interest rate raises and
diverting funds from the equity markets by increasing issues of government
debt.
That strategy must now be in doubt after the decision of Moody's and
Standard &amp; Poor's to downgrade Turkey's international credit rating, the
event that initially triggered the currency crisis.
Mr Gultekin's departure could cast an immediate shadow as Turkey attempts to
tap international debt markets.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>TRZ  Turkey, Middle East.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6011 Federal Reserve Banks.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
