<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Major set to resist right wing calls for reshuffle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major, the prime minister, is expected to warn the right wing of the
Tory party to stop undermining his leadership when he meets MPs from the 92
Group today.
The 92 Group deputation, led by Sir George Gardiner, will press for
promotion for up to eight rightwing ministers, half of whom would enter the
cabinet.
But last night the Tory right was backing away from demands for an early
cabinet reshuffle after Mr Major made it clear that he will not be hurried.
The group's main aim is to secure promotion for Mr Michael Portillo, chief
secretary to the Treasury, who is widely regarded as the most plausible
rightwing leadership contender.
Friends of the prime minister said he had agreed to meet the deputation to
show that his door is open to all party sections. But he will tell Sir
George that a reshuffle is 'far from his mind'.
The right believes that such a reshuffle would bring fresh blood into the
party leadership ahead of the local and European elections in May and June.
But support has ebbed since the demand was disclosed at the weekend. Many
Tory MPs said that it had merely reinforced the image of a party in turmoil.
One prominent Eurosceptic said the demand for a reshuffle had distracted
attention from the real divisions in the party over Europe and taxation
policy.
Others said it reflected continuing disillusionment with the prime
minister's leadership and anger over his failure to take a firm grip of the
party.
'The prime minister cannot regain the support of the right unless he rules
out a return to the European Monetary System - ever - and pledges to cut
taxes to the 1992 level before the next election,' said one.
The prime minister appeared to have sustained little damage from a weekend
interview in which Mr Norman Lamont, the former chancellor, was said to have
described Mr Major as 'weak and hopeless'.
Most MPs said the article had damaged Mr Lamont more than the prime minister
and senior Conservatives rallied to give public support, including Mr John
Redwood, the Welsh secretary.
However, the upheaval in the party was underlined by Lord Tebbit, a key
indicator of opinion on the Thatcherite right, who warned MPs not to panic.
Writing in the Daily Mail, Lord Tebbit said the economy was likely to
continue growing, but added that 'many Conservative MPs are determined to
panic again, as they did when they overthrew Margaret Thatcher. They would
do well to take a grip on themselves'.
Lamont attack, Page 7
Government close to retreat on single-tier councils, Page 20
</TEXT>
