<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / European bourses surge to record closing levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN PITT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
European equity markets yesterday swept to record highs after an active
day's trading, writes John Pitt.
Bullish sentiment was helped by a combination of factors: resolution of the
political crisis in Tokyo; good inflation data from the US on Friday; an
agreement restricting world aluminium production; and strength in car stocks
after the BMW-Rover deal.
Records were set in the UK with the FT-SE 100 index of leading companies
rising 1.3 per cent, to finish up 44.4 at 3,491.8; in France, where the
CAC-40 index added 1 per cent; in Switzerland, where the SMI index set its
fifth consecutive high; and in the Netherlands, Italy, Spain and Stockholm.
Only Germany failed to outstrip its previous best, although the Dax index
gained 2 per cent.
With hopes of a cut in European interest rates this month, further gains are
expected this week.
