<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / World Bond Markets: Frankfurt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bundesbank policy-making council meets on Thursday for the third time
this year and could well seize the opportunity to cut the discount rate for
the first time since October.
One positive factor is that inflation is coming back under control - the 3.4
per cent rise in prices in January reported last week was better than
expected and points to inflation down to below the 3 per cent for 1993 as a
whole.
Another is the Bundesbank's insistence that however dreadful the delayed
money supply figures for December turn out to be, this should be put down to
special factors.
The Bundesbank is encouraging markets to look ahead, saying that in January
M3 growth subsided.
Ms Alison Cottrell at Midland Global Markets Research in London says the
easing may come via a move to a 28-day variable-rate repo tender on Tuesday.
This would the first move from fixed-rate repos since early November and
could usher in a cut in 'official rates' on Thursday.
She argues that the recent weakness of the D-Mark will not discourage a rate
cut - 'the D-mark is weak precisely because interest rate easing is already
discounted'.
In the bund market further easing is not so well discounted and yields on
10-year bunds are likely to fall from Friday's 5.72 per cent level if the
Bundesbank acts.
</TEXT>
