<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / World Bond Markets: Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The last-minute passage of the coalition government's political reform bill
over the weekend may further dampen sentiment on the Japanese government
bond market.
Bond traders fear an economic stimulus package, likely to be announced this
week, will mean extra supply and a formal announcement may prompt
profit-taking.
The bond market has already been hit by fears of oversupply, triggered by a
recent government announcement that it will auction bonds outright rather
than with repurchase agreements.
Also, while the government has indicated that an income tax cut to boost the
slumping economy will ultimately be funded by an increase in consumption
taxes, an immediate rise is impossible. Last Saturday, Mr Morihiro Hosokawa,
prime minister, said he was not considering a sales tax hike at the moment,
and Mr Masayoshi Takemura, chief cabinet secretary, on Sunday said the
income tax cut will be funded by government bonds.
An income tax cut larger than Y6,000bn to Y7,000bn is likely to discourage
investors and profit-taking by institutional investors ahead of the March
book closing may also weigh on the bond market.
A recovery in the stock market is also negative for bonds, as hopes of a cut
in the official discount rate cut fade with a rally in share prices.
</TEXT>
