<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Emerging Markets: News round-up
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Strategy
Morgan Stanley's Barton Biggs notes in his latest comment on trends in
emerging markets that he considers 1994 should see a significant shift in
investor attitude. 'I think getting the country decision right will be much
more important . . . in 1993 if you caught the re-rating of one region,
Asia, you didn't have to worry much about countries, groups or stocks. I
think it's going to be much more challenging in 1994'.
The Emerging Markets Traders Association has elected Mr Alexis Rodzianko,
managing director at Chemical Bank, as chairman for 1994.
Latin America
With worries that a severe correction is imminent among Asia's equity
markets, Kleinwort Benson's Latin American team, headed by Roger Palmer, is
claiming that the region is less exposed 'to any bursting of the liquidity
bubble'.
This view is based on the fact that the Asian markets have been driven ever
higher by a wash of foreign, notably US, money, while the same funds'
exposure to Latin America has been small.
Therefore, when US interest rates finally rise, the argument goes, Latin
America should be immune to the fall-out.
Poland
Argument and counter-argument continue to swirl around the equity market
after last week's listing of Bank Slaski.
On the first day of trading the shares rocketed 1,250 per cent from the
offer price of 500,000 zlotys (Dollars 23).
Now many are saying that the price was too low, while the securities
commission is investigating the delay in processing applications, which has
left some unable to trade shares on the exchange.
On Friday the government minister responsible for privatising the country's
banking sector was sacked.
Indonesia
The government is considering privatising some state-owned companies on
foreign stock exchanges, although this is unlikely to include Garuda
Indonesia, the state airline, for the time being.
Fund growth
Emerging market funds could double in 1994, following rapid growth in the
last few years, Peter Jeffreys of Fund Research told a conference in London
last week.
The number of funds has risen from 65 in 1990 to 525 in 1994, he said, with
467 being equity funds with the remaining debt funds.
Some Dollars 120bn has been invested over the last decade, with more than 50
per cent of that total coming in 1993, he added.
Brazil
Smith Barney Shearson is understood to have raised its weighting of
Brazilian equities in its model Latin American portfolio from 10 per cent to
15 per cent.
'The economic and political outlook for Brazil shows signs of improving more
rapidly than we had originally anticipated,' the broker said.
It recommended buying on the market's recent weakness, which it said was due
to profit-taking after a strong recent rally.
Further coverage of emerging markets appears daily on the World Stock
Markets page.
</TEXT>
