<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Merger terms put Pounds 15m tag on Europa
Minerals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Terms for the three-way merger involving Europa Minerals value the UK-quoted
mining finance house at 62.6p a share or Pounds 15.4m, according to Samuel
Montagu, adviser to Burmine, the Australian gold company making the offer.
Europa's share price touched 57p at one stage on Friday after the news and
ended the day at 54p, up 12p.
Burmine is offering one of its shares for every two Europa ordinary and at
the same time, is making a 1-for-12 offer for Austmin Gold, an Australian
exploration company, valuing it at ADollars 15.5m (Pounds 7.4m).
Europa shareholders owning 52.5 per cent of the company said it was their
present intention to accept the Burmine bid. Europa's independent directors,
owning 2 per cent, recommend the offer and have irrevocably undertaken to
accept.
However, the three-way merger is challenged by an offer for Burmine by Mount
Edon, another Australian gold producer. Hearings by the Australian
authorities into technical challenges made by the companies are due to be
heard on February 7 and 8 and Burmine cannot move ahead with the three-way
deal until then.
The situation is made more complex because Mount Edon owns 22.6 per cent of
Burmine and 19.9 per cent of Europa. Europa owns 38.5 per cent of Burmine
and Austmin holds 19.8 per cent of Europa.
</TEXT>
