<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Japan plans Pounds 85bn economic stimulus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese government this week plans to follow its agreement on political
reform with a long-delayed package of tax cuts and government spending,
estimated to total at least Y14,000bn (Pounds 85bn).
Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, the prime minister, said at the weekend he aimed to
announce details by the end of the week. His seven-party coalition
government would seek co-operation on economic policy with the opposition
Liberal Democratic party.
The Nikkei rose more than 900 points by mid-morning today. Brokers said
investors welcomed the reform deal because it cleared political
uncertainties.
The economic package will come as a relief to the US and to Japanese
business organisations, which have been urging steps to relieve the
recession.
Until the weekend, the coalition's ability to act on the economy had been
paralysed by its attempts to win parliamentary agreement on plans to
redesign the electoral system and curb corruption. However, parliament on
Saturday voted in favour of a compromise on reform.
The newly confident coalition plans to hold elections 'anytime from this
autumn', said Mr Masayoshi Takemura, chief cabinet secretary. Ministers
responsible for the economy started work on the package at the weekend.
Early drafts envisage Y6,000bn to Y7,000bn in income and residential tax
cuts, plus Y4,000bn of government spending on infrastructure, according to
government officials quoted in the Japanese press. The package is also said
to include increased loans for housing and small businesses, plus possible
tax concessions for corporate land sales.
The government will draw up its budget for the coming fiscal year by
February 15, said Mrs Manae Kubota, director of the Economic Planning
Agency. It may expand an existing five-year programme of public works, worth
Y430,000bn. This week's package will be the fourth and possibly largest
pump-priming plan in 14 months.
Mr Hosokawa will have evidence of attempts to stimulate domestic demand when
he meets US president Bill Clinton in Washington on February 11. US-Japanese
trade relations have been strained by failure to agree on US demands that
Tokyo should accept numerical targets for reducing its trade surplus.
Historic agreement, Page 4
