FT  31 JAN 94 / Observer: Waxing matters
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Has Britain's recently married food minister, Nicholas Soames, taken his eye
off the ball? A set of draft regulations about mineral hydrocarbons are
bubbling to the surface in Soames' department and are causing a bit of a
stir amongst his buddies in the landed gentry.
Soames' officials have long been concerned about the harmful effects of
these compounds in foodstuffs. The plan is to ban almost all of them, but to
continue to permit their use in defeathering waterfowl, coating cheese and
in chewing gum.
All fine and dandy, except that the only two kinds of mineral hydrocarbon to
be allowed - high melting point microcrystalline wax and high sulphur
microcrystalline wax - are not, according to those who are supposed to know,
remotely suitable for the aforementioned processes.
