FT  31 JAN 94 / Letters to the Editor: Different pay deals for Channel train
drivers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr LEW ADAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Due to a misunderstanding, your report, 'Aslef wins 30 per cent pay
rise for Channel train drivers' (January 13) confused two agreements reached
by my union.
Annual salaries of between Pounds 20,500 and Pounds 25,000 have been agreed
for 55 Eurostar drivers working for the BR subsidiary, European Passenger
Services. They will take passengers from Waterloo International through the
Channel Tunnel to Paris and Brussels.
A separate deal has been reached with Railfreight Distribution under which
drivers of freight trains will receive a tunnel allowance of Pounds 90 a
week, double the current driver only allowance, on top of their BR basic
weekly wage of Pounds 210. They will take trains through the tunnel as far
as the terminal in Calais. We anticipate that such drivers will be able to
earn about Pounds 400 a week in total.
Aslef publicised these agreements, which compare with drivers' current
average earnings across British Rail of about Pounds 18,000, to show that we
intend to negotiate the best possible settlements for our members. Last
year's Aslef conference accepted that we may not be able to keep all drivers
on a uniform rate of pay nationwide when we face the possibility of having
to talk to some 41 different train operating companies under the
privatisation plans.
Lew Adams,
general secretary,
Associated Society of Locomotive Engineers and Firemen,
9 Arkwright Road,
London NW3 6AB
