<TEXT>
Sir, Richard Gourlay's otherwise excellent guide to recovery for survivors
of the recession (Management: The Growing Business, January 25) contains one
lamentable anachronism. The only way '. . .is to be able to turn round to
the customer and stick two fingers up' represents precisely the attitude
most likely to extinguish any glimmer of improved prospects.
We all have customers. What is called for from suppliers is to take the lead
in developing healthy and commercially sustainable partnerships with their
customers. This requires dedication to foster trust, and a mutual
understanding of requirements and ambitions.
Fingers should be put to work, not stuck up at customers.
