<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Those disinclined to believe that the Aids circus is driven by research
grants may want to watch Horizon which tells the story of 'Genie'. This
American girl spent the first 13 years of her life in silence, as a prisoner
in one room of her parents' house. When scientists found her there was
competition to use her to prove theories on language (she could hardly
speak) and development. Some of the researchers even fostered her. Then,
when the grant money ran out, Genie was sent to live in an institution,
where she has remained (8.00 BBC2).
Cutting Edge promises a report on the lives of British children who look
after disabled parents yet do not qualify for carers' allowances. In
Glasgow, for instance, a woman suffering from multiple sclerosis is in the
care of her children who are 13, 12 and 11 (9.00 C4).
Completing a Monday night trio of mournful current affairs programmes,
Panorama is the latest to have a go at the electricity-and-cancer story.
This time, instead of the dangers of electro -magnetic fields near pylons,
it is similar perils from sub-stations (9.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
