<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Arts: Regionals to the fore
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD FAIRMAN and MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The rise of regional orchestras was one of the outstanding features of the
1980s. At the weekend the London concert-halls played host to a pair of
orchestras, each of which comes from a self-proclaimed 'second city' in its
respective country - the NDR (North German Radio) Symphony Orchestra of
Hamburg and the City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra.
Both for its past and its present, Hamburg lays claim to be the cultural
centre of Germany. The number of publishing houses and record companies
which have their headquarters there testify to the city's importance in the
arts, but its musical life struggles to rival Munich or Berlin (indeed,
Berlin looks ever more dominant). It may well be that the NDR Symphony
Orchestra was aiming for a higher public profile when it appointed John
Eliot Gardiner as principal conductor in 1991.
With Gardiner's arrival there came a recording contract, which has ranged
from Brahms and Dvorak to Britten and Janacek. Unfortunately, his tenure in
Hamburg looks set to end this year, after a brief stay which is rumoured to
have been difficult. It has not, however, been unproductive. At its Royal
Festival Hall concert on Saturday the orchestra played with a combination of
clarity and intelligence that had Gardiner's stamp on it through and
through.
The programme consisted of two major romantic pieces: Rachmaninov's
Symphonic Dances and Mahler's Fourth Symphony. Both are complex orchestral
scores, in which Gardiner set out to make every note count. The razor-sharp
clarity that he gets from a symphony orchestra is remarkable to the point
where the Mahler became a bubbling cauldron of new and unexpected details.
What I missed was sensuality in the Rachmaninov, charm in the Mahler, though
Barbara Bonney was a delightfully bright-eyed soprano soloist in the latter.
While the Hamburg orchestra had been in Birmingham the night before, the
City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra had been in London, making one of its
periodic appearances at the Barbican. Again there was a vocal soloist who
gave a good account of herself, this time the mezzo Ann Murray, who sang
Berlioz's tragic scena La Mort de Cleopatre with a firm grasp of its
potential. A few years ago she would have been overparted in music like
this. Now both the voice and the personality have grown in stature.
Something similar might be said of the orchestra, which was in good form
under Mark Elder, its principal guest conductor. Their performance of
Sibelius's First Symphony also had plenty of character, as Elder dug away at
the rhythms to create climaxes that became nearly obssessive in their drive.
It was very different from Simon Rattle's Sibelius with his orchestra, less
atmosphere, more intensity. The programme noted that Rattle's recording was
on sale upstairs - rather tactlessly, I thought.
Jonathan Lloyd, an English composer in his mid-40s still far too little
known in the wider musical world, has fulfilled a commission from the London
Philharmonic Orchestra in a way that should aid in righting the balance.
Committed Lloyd-followers long ago learned to relish his music above all for
its wit - achieved not through farce, hyperbole or heavily jokey contrast,
but through fresh and sometimes slyly hilarious use of a highly individual
musical language, in which the popular and the recherche are jostled and
blended with genial sleight-of-hand.
Lloyd's Waiting for Gozo, for the London Sinfonietta, and his recent score
for the Hitchcock silent film Blackmail are just two examples of this
'personal' quality at its most quirkily original. Tolerance - the LPO's new
big-orchestra piece, given on Thursday its premiere at the Royal Festival
Hall under Franz Welser-Most - seems to me a captivating third, on an
orchestral scale larger than most of his previous ensemble compositions.
The title is intended to suggest the 'co-operative anarchy' that rules its
scheme, with different groups of orchestral voices constantly snatching the
limelight and then ceding it, and with a continual undercurrent of
contrasted comment - sometimes wrily amiable, sometimes acerbic - from
others. Snatches of Prokofiev-like bustle are tossed into the mixture, later
to be exchanged for Tchaikovskian melodic sumptuousness and cell-like
outbursts of Janacekian fractiousness.
The circus imagery that Lloyd also invokes in his programme note is
particularly to be sensed in the percussion punctuation: ringmaster, as it
were, of an unfolding entertainment made up of many interlocked diversions.
What is actually achieved beneath the amusing variety of sounds and rhythmic
patterns is an unexpectedly substantial 20-minute concerto for orchestra,
one which tests each department in enjoyably taxing ways.
In their first go at Tolerance, Welser-Most and the LPO got round the notes
efficiently enough but only intermittently conveyed the wry good humour in
their connection, and in Lloyd's use of quotation and pastiche. There is
room here for greater interpretative freedom, sharper responsiveness: future
LPO performances, of which I hope there will be a good number, must surely
help these players.
</TEXT>
<XX>
