<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Television adverts for children defended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A ban on television advertisements during children's programmes would be an
'unwarranted curtailment of freedom' as well as removing funding for such
programmes, a report warns today
The study was commissioned by the Advertising Association and conducted by
Professor Patrick Barwise of the London Business School. It was commissioned
after a call last year from the National Food Alliance for the government to
consider an advertising ban during children's television.
The alliance - a research and lobbying group supported by, among others, the
British Dental Association, trade unions, the Institute of Child Health, and
the National Farmers' Union - said it was concerned about the effect of TV
advertisements on children's diet.
The alliance said advertisements for children were dominated by sugary and
fatty foods, such as pre-sweetened cereals, confectionery, fast foods and
soft drinks 'which neither encourage healthy choices nor promote a varied
and healthy diet'.
Prof Barwise's report accuses the alliance of publishing a 'poorly
researched and one-sided' document. He rejects its claim that advertising is
a strong influence on children's consumption of particular types of food and
drink. 'What advertisers try to do is encourage people to choose their
brand. This has little or no effect on total category sales.'
Ms Sue Dibb, author of the alliance's report, said of the Advertising
Association's study: 'I've heard the arguments many times before - they tend
to be trotted out when the advertisers are under attack.'
Children, Advertising and Nutrition. The Advertising Association, Abford
House, 15 Wilton Road, London SW1V 1NJ. Free.
</TEXT>
