<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Troubled electrical chain continues trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Clydesdale Group, the Glasgow-based electrical retail chain which went into
receivership on Friday night, is to continue trading while receivers follow
up expressions of interest from potential buyers.
The company was defeated by persistent under-capitalisation, poor sales and
a costly expansion programme in England, according to one of the receivers,
Mr Malcolm Shierson of accountants Grant Thornton. Clydesdale claimed to
have the third-largest share of the UK electrical goods retail market, after
Dixons and Comet.
The board of Clydesdale asked a consortium of four banks - Bank of Scotland,
Royal Bank of Scotland, Barclays and NM Rothschild - to call in receivers
after they refused to provide an emergency funding package of Pounds 4m.
The banks are owed about Pounds 35m, of which nearly half is owed to Royal
Bank. Total debts have not been quantified.
The company had resorted to the banks after attempts to raise money from its
main shareholders, led by Standard Life and Scottish Amicable, had failed.
The joint receivers, Mr Shierson, Mr Allan Griffiths and Mr Donald
McGruther, have arranged for the group to continue trading for the time
being. They have secured support from the banks, from Cornhill Insurance -
which will underwrite the product warranties - and from British Midland
airline, which will continue honouring cheap flight vouchers from Clydesdale
customers.
Mr Griffiths said the receivers had already received three expressions of
interest from large organisations and expected to receive more. The
receivers intended to sell the group as a whole. It is likely to appeal to
electricity companies anxious to expand their retail network.
Clydesdale, which employs about 1,500 people, has about 100 high street
stores in Scotland and 20 out-of-town stores in England. In the year to
March 31 1993 it had sales of Pounds 141m on which it made an operating
profit of Pounds 5.6m.
Last June it abandoned a flotation after an audit by Arthur Andersen
revealed that stock had been overvalued. Mr Jim Boyd, finance director, left
the company.
The failure of the flotation, which would have raised Pounds 30m, meant that
the group's problems of under-capitalisation intensified. The expansion
programme had been based on the assumption that the recession was ending and
that the flotation would proceed.
Over the weekend Royal Bank of Scotland angrily rejected accusations by Mr
Henk van Eck, Clydesdale's chief executive, that it had blocked the bank
rescue package. It said the members of the syndicate were unanimous in
refusing to advance the Pounds 4m.
Mr van Eck, a company rescue specialist, joined Clydesdale in 1985, taking
51 per cent of the shares.
</TEXT>
