<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Stores curb the urge to expand: Neil Buckley and Vanessa
Houlder examine the end of a building spree by the supermarket groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY and VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Decisions by the UK's three largest supermarket groups to write down land
and building costs and trim their opening programmes signal an end to the
store-building free-for-all of the late 1980s and early 1990s.
The pace in future will be less frenetic and the prices paid for land less
astronomic. The retail scene has changed markedly from 1991 when the big
three were spending up to Pounds 2.5bn a year between them on expansion, and
were prepared to pay huge premiums to secure prime sites.
Since then, increasing price competition and market saturation has sparked
fears in the City that superstore groups would be unable to sustain their
margins and returns on capital. Those fears - coupled with the slump in the
property market - led to increasing pressure on store chains to rein back
expansion and depreciate buildings and land.
Asda, the UK's fourth-largest grocer, halted its expansion programme 18
months ago and wrote down its property and fixed assets by Pounds 319m. Yet
it took until last month before Argyll, the UK's number three, announced it
would depreciate buildings at 2.5 per cent a year, and cut capital spending
from Pounds 650m to Pounds 550m this year.
Two weeks ago Tesco followed suit with a similar depreciation policy for
buildings, as well as a decision to write down the 'premiums' it had paid
for its land - the difference between the price paid and the alternative use
value - over 25 years. With the latter charge put at Pounds 32m this year,
there was an implicit admission that the group had overpaid, by a massive
Pounds 800m, on its land.
Tesco also made an Pounds 85m write-down on land it had decided to sell
rather than use for new stores. It said it would cut capital spending from
Pounds 750m this year to Pounds 450m-Pounds 500m in 1996-97, and its
store-expansion programme from 31 to 20 over the same period, with the
emphasis shifting to smaller superstores and its new Metro city-centre
format.
Finally last Friday, J. Sainsbury said it would depreciate stores at the
slower rate of 2 per cent a year, and make a one-off write-down of the
Pounds 365m it had overpaid for land. Some Pounds 60m of that charge
referred to surplus land which it, too, had decided to sell.
It said it would continue to open 20 grocery superstores a year for four
years, but beyond that the pace might slow.
Mr Jeremy Alun-Jones, retail analyst at Lehman Brothers, said: 'The biggest
thing about all these announcements is that they recognise the fact that
superstores don't last for ever.'
They also reflect a decline in the top end of the property market from more
than Pounds 2m an acre in 1991 to between Pounds 1m and Pounds 1.5m an acre
now, according to Erdman Lewis, chartered surveyors.
Some agents believe, however, that the decline in prices has come to a halt
as a result of strong demand from other types of out-of-town retailer.
After years when bidding battles between supermarket chains pushed site
prices above the reach of other purchasers, there is now strong competition
for the best sites from operators of retail warehouses. Tenant demand for
warehouses has been buoyant as these large out-of-town stores have appealed
to a growing number of retailers. The warehouses sell goods ranging from
furniture to office supplies.
Another factor that could sustain prices would be a tightening of planning
controls, which would reduce the supply of potential sites. Mr John Gummer,
environment secretary, recently indicated that he wished to discourage
development on greenfield sites on the edge of cities, so as to help
revitalise town centres.
The sites that are best expected to retain their values are those
surrounding prosperous towns where development was constrained by
restrictive planning policies in the 1980s.
</TEXT>
