<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / De-recognition expected to rise
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Union de-recognition is likely to increase this year although the trend is
attributed to practical factors rather than hostility towards unions, says
an industrial relations report published today.
Of those companies which admitted de-recognising unions in a survey by
Industrial Relations Services, the independent research organisation, most
said that a wish to establish a closer link between pay and performance was
the main motivation. De-recognition entails switching from national to local
bargaining.
Pembrokeshire NHS Trust took issue with the report's belief that it had
de-recognised unions. Mr Keith Brown, head of personnel, said it still
recognised its 16 unions for the purposes of representation and
consultation. He added that Pembrokeshire was one of the few trusts to
organise its pay system locally. 'The rest of them are wimps,' he said.
</TEXT>
