<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Fiscal squeeze 'will cut growth'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The two Budgets of 1993 will reduce UK economic growth by between 0.5 per
cent and 1 per cent a year for the next three years, say accountants and
management consultants Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
It says the combined effect will be a fiscal squeeze of about 1.6 per cent
of gross domestic product in 1994-95, rising to about 3 per cent in 1996-97.
This is a greater impact than that of Lord Howe's 1981 Budget and represents
'the most severe fiscal squeeze in the UK since 1945'.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand does not expect economic growth to average more than 2 per
cent to 2.5 per cent over the next three years.
Tax debate, Page 8
