<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Barclays chief to be paid Pounds 737,500
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Martin Taylor, the new chief executive of Barclays, the largest high
street bank, is to be paid at least Pounds 737,500 this year including a
bonus of Pounds 150,000, the bank disclosed yesterday, John Gapper writes.
Mr Taylor, 41, a former Financial Times journalist who was recruited by
Barclays from Courtaulds Textiles, of which he was chairman, will be among
the highest paid UK bank directors as a result of the two-year contract
which started this month.
Mr Taylor's contract will give him a basic salary of Pounds 500,000 for each
of the two years. In the second year he will receive a bonus determined by
Barclays' normal directors' bonus formula, and he will revert to a one-year
rolling contract in 1996.
In addition to the basic salary and the Pounds 500,000 bonus in the first
year of the contract, Mr Taylor will receive contributions to two pension
schemes totalling Pounds 87,500.
</TEXT>
