<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Fears grow over the rise and rise of 'petty councillors'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, JOHN AUTHERS and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Heagney brothers, co-directors of the A. Heagney chain of supermarkets
in the north-east, think they have seen the future of local government
reorganisation. They are convinced it does not work.
They are not alone. Businesses in most of the areas of the country so far
touched by the local government commission's review initially welcomed
reorganisation as an opportunity to save public money and to cut their own
compliance costs by reducing the number of councils they had to deal with.
But now they fear reorganisation will cost extra money and confuse their
position still further. Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the
Confederation of British Industry, wrote to Mr John Gummer, the environment
secretary, saying the review could become 'an expensive hobby for the
government', and 'an exer-cise in bureaucratic job creation across the
country'.
The CBI supports the general principle of unitary councils - where the
two-tier system of county and district councils is replaced by all-purpose
councils - provided they are of 'reasonable size'. The issue of strategic
planning is paramount. They argue that authorities need to have sufficient
clout for economic development, planning and transport.
Proposals for dismantling the unpopular county of Cleveland and replacing it
with four unitary authorities have met with a particularly fierce response.
Mr Mike Heagney, one of the two brothers who runs the Pounds 6.5m annual
turnover chain, believes he is about to fall victim to the kind of
parochialism that he and others in business fear will gain the upper hand if
the county is divided into four units, as the government is recommending.
He says the success of his shop in Berwick Hills, one of Middlesbrough's
less affluent housing estates, is threatened by a development approved last
week by Middlesbrough council. The Pounds 13m scheme, championed by the
council as part of its City Challenge urban regeneration initiative,
involves the construction of a 78,000 sq ft Morrison's superstore.
To make way for the store and its 788-space car park in the heart of the
30-year-old estate, Berwick Hills' swimming baths, library, community
centre, housing office, youth club, church, church hall and vicarage will
all have to be demolished and rebuilt.
'It's being decided by petty, parochial councillors,' Mr Heagney claims.
'The opposition's been enormous and the councillors have totally ignored
it.'
Cleveland council currently has responsibility for highways and for
formulating the county's structure plan, and opposes the Berwick Hills
scheme on both these grounds.
The districts deny they are parochial. Nor do they accept that four unitary
districts would weaken structural planning controls. A joint committee of
the four unitary authorities would be set up, says Middlesbrough's chief
economic development and planning officer Mr Tony Noble, to deal with any
proposed departures from the structure plan and other strategic issues.
'There's no greater danger of succumbing to parochialism than any other
structure,' he says. The superstore scheme, he says, will enhance the
overall vitality and viability of Berwick Hills.
Business feelings are similarly strong in Avon and Somerset, which are to be
split into seven unitary authorities. 'I've never encountered such a dog's
breakfast before,' says Mr Chris Curtis, director of the CBI in the
south-west. 'Absolutely no good to be said for it, any way at all.'
The Bristol Chamber of Commerce and Initiative describes the business
community as 'outraged' by the recommendations which would have a
'disastrous impact' on the region.
Again strategic planning is at issue. Bristol will be unitary, but
restricted to its present historic boundaries. The CBI, Institute of
Directors and Bristol Chamber had lobbied for an expanded Bristol to include
the urban area outside its present boundaries.
Most local managing directors, according to a survey by the Bristol chamber,
believe the commission's proposals would leave the city too small and
under-resourced.
But Mr John Irwin, a Teesside director of chartered surveyors Storey Sons &amp;
Parker, provides a typical business judgment on the review so far: 'It's a
fantastic opportunity to start again. But that opportunity is being missed.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9121 Legislative Bodies.
</IN>
