<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Farmers' earnings increase by 60%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Farmers saw their income rise by about Pounds 1.1bn last year, an increase
of 60 per cent on the level of earnings in 1992, according to figures to be
published by the government today.
The rise in farm receipts was almost wholly due to the devaluation of
sterling in September 1992 which increased the value of European Union
agricultural payments for UK farmers. Overall output from the industry
slipped by 2 per cent during the year.
Farmers producing milk, arable crops, beef and sheep all benefited from the
devaluation of the pound. Cereal growers gained from higher subsidies paid
as part of the EU's farm reform programme.
Pig farmers and vegetable growers did not share in the overall return of
confidence to the sector. Pig producers saw prices for pork slump because of
European overproduction in the past two years. At the same time, their costs
rose because of higher grain prices caused by the devaluation.
Vegetable growers have seen their margins come under pressure with receipts
falling in real terms for the past three to four years. Demand for fresh
vegetables has also dropped.
With farm incomes up substantially and most farm costs remaining steady
because of low inflation and low interest rates, many farmers are beginning
to invest in their business again. The National Farmers' Union estimates
that investment rose by 30 per cent last year and is set to continue to rise
this year.
In addition, farmers reduced borrowings by 5 per cent. Mr David Naish, NFU
president, said the increase in farm incomes came after many years of
declining earnings and very little investment.
Farmers could soon be under pressure again through the effects of the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
</TEXT>
