<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Coopers highlights fiscal squeeze
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The two Budgets of 1993 will reduce UK economic growth by between 0.5 and 1
per cent a year for the next three years, say accountants and management
consultants Coopers &amp; Lybrand, Philip Coggan writes.
It says the combined effect will be a fiscal squeeze of about 1.6 per cent
of gross domestic product in 1994-95, rising to around 3 per cent in
1996-97. This is a greater impact than Sir Geoffrey Howe's 1981 Budget and
represents 'the most severe fiscal squeeze in the UK since 1945'.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand does not expect economic growth to average more than 2-2.5
per cent over the next three years. On that assumption, and on the belief
that the government may find it difficult to reduce public spending and may
indulge in a pre-election tax-cutting Budget, the report argues that the
chancellor's aim of restoring the public sector finances to balance by the
end of the 1990s may not be achievable.
Tax debate, Page 8
