<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Derecognition of unions expected to rise this year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Union derecognition is likely to increase this year although the trend is
attributed to practical factors rather than hostility towards unions,
according to an industrial relations report published today.
Companies featured in the survey by Industrial Relations Services, the
independent research organisation, largely dismissed hostility towards
unions in their decisions.
Most of the companies which admitted derecognising unions said that a desire
to establish a closer link between pay and performance was the main reason
for doing so.
Some companies, such as Yorkshire Electricity Group, cited the need to
rationalise bargaining arrangements with fewer unions. Only a small
proportion blamed poor management-union relations and one company said the
impetus had come from the workforce.
Of the 98 which responded to the survey, 25 said they had removed collective
bargaining rights in some cases.
Many of the cases involved recently privatised public companies or National
Health Service trusts. North American companies also featured strongly.
Alcan Consumer Products in Amersham, Buckinghamshire, which last year
derecognised the TGWU general union, said the move had been at the request
of employees since only a fifth of the workforce had been in the union.
The union was told it would be derecognised unless it increased its numbers.
But Alcan said it failed to do so.
British Telecommunications derecognised collective bargaining for 7,500 over
managerial grades between 1990 and 1992 by the introduction of personal
contracts. The company said: 'We wanted to create clear links between
individual managers and the company and to promote greater flexibility in
the terms and salaries we could offer.'
Pembrokeshire NHS Trust took issue with the report's belief that it had
derecognised unions.
Mr Keith Brown, head of personnel, said the trust still recognised its 16
unions for the purposes of representation and consultation. Before becoming
a trust, the authority had recognised national collective bargaining which
meant that no local bargaining arrangement had existed to derecognise, he
argued.
He said: 'We don't get involved in a national pay bargaining. We decide for
ourselves what people get paid. I'm all for it.'
He added that Pembrokeshire was one of the few trusts to organise its pay
system locally. 'The rest of them are wimps,' he said.
IRS Employment Trends 553, Industrial Relations Services, 18-20 Highbury
Place, London N5 1QP. By subscription.
</TEXT>
