<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Local government reorganisation in England
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first plans for local government reorganisation in England will reach
parliament next month, at the start of a process which will last into next
year, John Authers writes.
Mr Michael Heseltine, as environment secretary, devised the review system to
ensure a consensus for all proposals. But it also provides opponents with
frequent opportunities to block reforms.
Mr John Gummer, the current environment secretary, cannot present any
restructuring plans to parliament unless they have first been recommended by
the Local Government Commission, chaired by Sir John Banham.
Sir John's review is working on a county-by-county basis and has so far
presented formal plans for only 10 counties. The remainder do not have to be
completed until the end of this year.
Mr Gummer then has limited powers to amend plans by altering boundaries, but
if he wishes to make more drastic alterations, such as changing the total
number of councils, he must send the proposals back to Sir John.
Once Mr Gummer has approved a plan, orders for each county must go before
parliament to be debated and approved by both houses. If any are voted down,
the status quo will continue for them.
</TEXT>
