<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / US grants limited visa to Sinn Fein leader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE, ROLAND RUDD and MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN, LONDON, BELFAST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gerry Adams, the president of Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing, has
been granted a visa to enter the US, in a dramatic reversal of Washington
policy.
Up to now, the US has sought to mirror British policy regarding Mr Adams,
who is excluded from entering the British mainland.
In a statement, the White House said the action was taken because Mr Adams
had made 'constructive comments' on renouncing violence.
'It is in the interests of peace that the US reach out to Mr Adams to press
him to go forward,' it added.
He will attend a conference in New York tomorrow on Northern Ireland
organised by the North American Committee on Foreign Policy, an independent
but influential think-tank with several former secretaries of state among
its members. The leaders of all Ulster's main political parties have also
been invited to attend.
Downing Street said last night: 'Adams has said he wants to end violence and
on that basis he is being admitted to New York to attend a conference. Sinn
Fein will be judged on its deeds. It must renounce violence permanently and
immediately.'
The news was welcomed by Mr Joe Hendron, West Belfast MP for the mainly
Roman Catholic Social Democratic and Labour party, but it provoked an angry
response from unionist politicians.
Mr Ken Maginnis, deputy leader of the Ulster Unionist party, who had been
'on standby' to attend the New York conference, said he would not be going
as long as Mr Adams or any Sinn Fein 'proxies' were there.
He was 'disappointed' by the US decision, 'as it would appear the US
government is more interested in pressuring Her Majesty's government to
concede to violence than in actually encouraging the peace process'.
The US State Department had said last week the decision on granting a visa
would depend on whether Mr Adams would 'publicly renounce violence and
support the joint declaration' issued in December by London and Dublin.
Speaking on Irish TV yesterday evening, before he received news of the visa
approval, Mr Adams said he had had an interview with US embassy officials
last week but denied that he was called on to make such prior commitments.
Later, welcoming the visa decision, he said: 'My purpose in going to the US
is to advance the cause of peace.'
Mr Adams will apparently be allowed to enter the US for 48 hours, but will
be restricted to travel within 25 miles of New York and will be barred from
fund-raising activities.
There has apparently been intense debate in Washington, with Irish-American
politicians divided over the issue.
Senator Edward Kennedy, whose sister, Mrs Jean Kennedy-Smith, is the US
ambassador in Dublin, is thought to have been lobbying the State Department
in favour of the visa approval. Last night he welcomed the decision.
It also emerged at the weekend that Mr Albert Reynolds, the Irish prime
minister, has replied to Mr Adams following a request from him for
clarification of the Downing Street joint declaration.
The letter is thought to contain Mr Reynolds' views on the shape of likely
progress after an end to the IRA's campaign of violence.
</TEXT>
