<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 94 / Tory unrest threatens council reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is facing mounting opposition from Conservative MPs opposed
to plans to replace the dual structure of English local government with
single tier, all-purpose councils.
More than a dozen Conservative MPs - more than enough to wipe out the
government's overall majority of 17 - say they are seriously concerned about
proposals emerging from the local government commission, chaired by Sir John
Banham.
Two told the Financial Times on the record that they would vote against the
government unless it dropped proposed changes or maked them more acceptable
to local people. Others made the same threat privately.
The strongest centres of unrest are in Yorkshire and the West Country, where
the commission's proposals are most advanced. But unease is also emerging
among shire MPs from the Tory heartlands in East Anglia and the south-east.
The emerging divisions over local government came as a string of senior
Tories yesterday called for unity behind Mr John Major's leadership.
Backbench opposition is forcing the government to consider watering down
plans to restrict student unions and overhaul the police in the face of
opposition within its own ranks. Sir Marcus Fox, chairman of the 1922
committee of Conservative MPs, and a Yorkshire MP, says backbenchers are
'generally very concerned'.
The picture is complicated by the High Court's decision on Friday that the
government cannot insist on the abolition of county councils except in
exceptional cases. Tories opposing the proposals are likely to use the
ruling to press the government to reconsider its plans or risk costly legal
challenges.
The strongest signs of rebellion are coming from Somerset. Mr Tom King
(Bridgwater), a former cabinet minister, said he had 'registered deep
concern' with Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary. Two MPs - Mr David
Heathcoat-Amery (Wells) and Mr David Nicholson (Taunton) - said they would
vote against the proposals.
Mr Heathcoat-Amery said: 'The commission has not understood the complexities
of our small but complex county, and we have taken the view that this cannot
go ahead without the support of the public, which it is very clear it does
not have.'
Mr Anthony Steen (South Hams), who will meet Mr Gummer today for talks on
the future of Devon's local authorities, said anxiety was widespread among
West Country MPs.
He said: 'I doubt that the government will be able to implement these
changes because the party will never back it.'
Yorkshire MPs are not yet threatening open rebellion. But Mr William Hague
(Richmond), a junior social security minister, Mr Robert Banks (Harrogate)
and Mr Michael Alison (Selby) all say they oppose the commission's plans to
restore the ancient North Riding. 'I am not prepared to make any warlike
noises yet about voting against the government,' said Mr Alison. 'But Mr
Gummer is aware that there is a lot of disillusionment.'
Other MPs said there was concern about the possible abolition of county
councils or the proposed boundaries of unitary authorities in a number of
other counties, including Lincolnshire, Hampshire, Kent, and Norfolk.
The first orders for reorganisation, in Cleveland and the Isle of Wight, are
due to be presented to parliament next month.
They should be followed within weeks, if Mr Gummer consents to Sir John's
proposals, by much more controversial plans to reorganise Avon and Somerset,
and Humberside and North Yorkshire.
Business fears, Page 6
Tactical retreat, Page 7
</TEXT>
